%S A397495 1,6,15,65,114,264,369,671,1386,1695,2934,4020,4641,6095,8814,12209,
%T A397495 13530,17985,21455,23364,29679,34481,42636,55344,62550,66351,74465,
%U A397495 78786,87864,125055,137345,157284,164289,202686,210975,237354,265761,285935,318114
%N A397495 Number of quadruples (a,b,c,d) of nonzero quadratic residues modulo prime(n) such that a + b == c + d (mod prime(n)).
%C A397495 a(n) is the number of ordered quadruples (a,b,c,d) of nonzero quadratic residues mod p (p = prime(n)) with a + b congruent to c + d. Equivalently a(n) = Sum_x r(x)^2 where r(x) = #{(a,b) in QR^2 : a+b == x (mod p)} is the number of ways x is a sum of two quadratic residues; this quantity is called the additive energy of the set of quadratic residues.
%F A397495 a(n) = (p-1) * (p^2 - 2*p + 7 + 2*Legendre(-1, p)) / 16, where p = prime(n).
%F A397495 a(n) = (p-1) * (p^2-2*p+9) / 16 for p == 1 (mod 4) and (p-1) * (p^2-2*p+5) / 16 for p == 3 (mod 4).
%e A397495 For n=3, p = prime(3) = 5. The nonzero quadratic residues mod 5 are {1, 4}. The ordered pairs (a,b) give sums (mod 5): 1+1=2, 1+4=0, 4+1=0, 4+4=3, so r(0)=2, r(2)=1, r(3)=1. The additive energy is 2^2 + 1^2 + 1^2 = 6, hence a(3) = 6.
%o A397495 (SageMath)
%o A397495 def a(n):
%o A397495     p = nth_prime(n)
%o A397495     QR = set((x*x) % p for x in range(1, p))
%o A397495     from collections import Counter
%o A397495     r = Counter((u + v) % p for u in QR for v in QR)
%o A397495     return sum(c*c for c in r.values())
%o A397495 print([a(n) for n in range(2, 41)])
%K A397495 nonn,easy,new
%O A397495 2,2
